Class FakeApplet

  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.awt.image.ImageObserver, java.awt.MenuContainer, java.io.Serializable, javax.accessibility.Accessible
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    MyApplet
    class FakeApplet
extends java.awt.Panel
    Emulates the old Applet behaviour which is no longer supported. This class serves to provide the same sort of hooks (`init`, `start`, `paint`, `stop`, and `destroy`) that the Applet mechanism used to provide, while automatically handling all of the Frame construction, setup, and teardown.
    Author:
    Duane Leslie

    • Constructor Detail

      • FakeApplet

        public FakeApplet()
        Create a FakeApplet of size 600x300 pixels. When this constructor is called the Applet will immediately construct itself, and then on the Event Dispatch Thread it will run its `init()` method, display itself, and then run the `start()` method.

      • FakeApplet

        public FakeApplet​(int width,
                  int height)
        Create a FakeApplet of a custom size. Note that the size is the frame size, not the canvas size (which will be smaller due to decorations.
        Parameters:
        width - width of the frame in pixels
        height - height of the frame in pixels

    • Method Detail

      • init

        public void init()
        Automatically run after the constructor completes, but before any other method.

      • start

        public void start()
        Called whenever the Applet is (re)started. This includes both initially, but also after a `stop()` call when the Applet is resumed (for example, after being minimized).

      • paint

        public void paint​(java.awt.Graphics g)
        Called for every frame update to handle any custom drawing. It is important to note that 'widgets' automatically paint themselves and so don't need to be handled here.
        Overrides:
        paint in class java.awt.Container

      • stop

        public void stop()
        Called whenever the Applet is stopped. This includes both when it is minimized, and also just before destruction when it is being closed.

      • destroy

        public void destroy()
        Automatically run just before the Applet is destroyed.

      • sync

        public static void sync()
        Wait until the Event Dispatch Thread is empty before proceeding. This ensures that anything that is still trying to happen has happened before proceeding. This is most important for ensuring that the 'init()' routine is complete before trying to interact with the applet.

      • waitForClose

        public void waitForClose()
        Provides a mechanism to hold the main thread of the program until this Applet has closed. This doesn't need to be used for correct operation of an Applet program, but if you would like to retrieve some data once the Applet has closed (i.e. to save state or print out some statistics) in the main thread (instead of using the Applet's `destroy()` method) then you need to use this method to 'block' the main thread.
